1
00:00:03,371 --> 00:00:06,848
But what are we told is dīkṣā 
in the famous śloka?

2
00:00:06,956 --> 00:00:10,340
Dīkṣā-kāle bhakta kare
ātma-samarpaṇa (Cc: 1.4.192-93).

3
00:00:10,523 --> 00:00:12,898
[Right Time, Right Guru]

4
00:00:13,361 --> 00:00:17,777
When there's ātma-samarpaṇa—
totally offering oneself,

5
00:00:17,777 --> 00:00:22,773
completely offering oneself 
in service.

6
00:00:22,773 --> 00:00:26,070
So from one perspective, 
we could say, also,

7
00:00:26,070 --> 00:00:35,071
until you've fully offered yourself,
are you fully initiated?

8
00:00:35,732 --> 00:00:37,960
Think: dīkṣā-kāle bhakta kare
ātma-samarpaṇa;

9
00:00:37,960 --> 00:00:41,903
it’s the time
when you fully give yourself.

10
00:00:41,903 --> 00:00:46,060
So Guru Mahārāj will say that
mainly in the modern times,

11
00:00:46,060 --> 00:00:53,179
we’re employing tantric dīkṣā,
which means in this sense

12
00:00:53,179 --> 00:01:00,315
that someone is being given 
the opportunity to become qualified.

13
00:01:00,315 --> 00:01:04,367
In the classic example, 
Hari-bhakti-vilāsa,

14
00:01:04,367 --> 00:01:07,809
we have the qualified Guru,
and the qualified disciple;

15
00:01:07,809 --> 00:01:11,412
they're examining one another
perfectly for one year—

16
00:01:11,412 --> 00:01:17,566
śravaṇa-daśa, varaṇa-daśa,
āpana, prapanna, etc.

17
00:01:17,566 --> 00:01:23,194
It’s interesting, there was talk
about the proper time of year

18
00:01:23,194 --> 00:01:26,286
to become initiated—
the proper month,

19
00:01:26,286 --> 00:01:31,593
the proper day of the week, 
the proper time of the day,

20
00:01:31,593 --> 00:01:36,638
and gradually you start reading
so many qualifications,

21
00:01:36,638 --> 00:01:38,737
“Is this ever possible?”

22
00:01:38,737 --> 00:01:42,919
But if you are patient enough
to read to the end

23
00:01:45,305 --> 00:01:53,392
it says, “However, if you find a qualified
Guru and he's willing to initiate you:

24
00:01:53,392 --> 00:01:58,376
that’s the right time, the right place,
the right everything.”

